# 6. Embedded Documents vs References

One of the most important MongoDB design decisions.

---

## Embedded Documents

Store related data inside the same document.

Example:

```javascript
{
  "_id": 1,
  "title": "MongoDB Guide",
  "comments": [
    {
      "user": "Praveen",
      "text": "Great article"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Advantages

* Faster reads
* Single query retrieval
* No joins required

### Disadvantages

* Larger document size
* Potential data duplication

---

## References

Store related document IDs.

Users Collection:

```javascript
{
  "_id": ObjectId("101"),
  "name": "Praveen"
}
```

Posts Collection:

```javascript
{
  "_id": ObjectId("201"),
  "title": "MongoDB Guide",
  "author": ObjectId("101")
}
```

### Advantages

* Better scalability
* Avoids duplication
* Easier updates

### Disadvantages

* Additional queries
* More complex retrieval

---

## When to Embed

Use embedding when:

* Data is small
* Data is frequently accessed together
* Relationship is tightly coupled

Examples:

* User Address
* User Preferences
* Product Specifications

---

## When to Reference

Use references when:

* Data grows large
* Many-to-many relationships exist
* Independent updates are required

Examples:

* Users and Posts
* Students and Courses
* Orders and Products

---

# 7. Relationship Modeling

## One-to-One

User and Profile

```javascript
{
  "_id": 1,
  "name": "Praveen",
  "profile": {
    "bio": "Developer"
  }
}
```

Usually embedded.

---

## One-to-Many

User and Posts

```javascript
{
  "_id": 1,
  "name": "Praveen"
}
```

```javascript
{
  "title": "Post 1",
  "author": 1
}
```

Usually references.

---

## Many-to-Many

Student and Courses

```javascript
{
  "name": "Praveen",
  "courses": [101, 102]
}
```

```javascript
{
  "title": "MongoDB",
  "students": [1, 2]
}
```

Uses references.

