# 8. Mongoose ODM

ODM stands for:

```text
Object Data Modeling
```

Mongoose is a Node.js library that provides schema-based interaction with MongoDB.

---

## Benefits

* Schema enforcement
* Validation
* Middleware support
* Cleaner code
* Population support

---

## Interview Answer

Mongoose is an ODM library for MongoDB that provides schema-based modeling, validation, middleware, and simplified database interactions.

---

# 9. Mongoose Schema

A Schema defines document structure.

Example:

```javascript
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  name: String,
  age: Number,
  email: String
});
```

Responsibilities:

* Define fields
* Validation rules
* Default values
* Constraints

---

# 10. Mongoose Model

A Model is created from a Schema.

```javascript
const User = mongoose.model("User", userSchema);
```

Used for CRUD operations.

```javascript
User.create()
User.find()
User.findById()
User.updateOne()
User.deleteOne()
```

---

## Schema vs Model

| Schema            | Model              |
| ----------------- | ------------------ |
| Blueprint         | Database Interface |
| Defines Structure | Performs CRUD      |
| No DB Operations  | DB Operations      |

---

# 11. Schema Validation

## Required

```javascript
name: {
  type: String,
  required: true
}
```

## Default

```javascript
status: {
  type: String,
  default: "Pending"
}
```

## Min

```javascript
age: {
  type: Number,
  min: 18
}
```

## Max

```javascript
age: {
  type: Number,
  max: 60
}
```

## Enum

```javascript
role: {
  type: String,
  enum: ["Admin", "User"]
}
```

---

## Complete Example

```javascript
const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  name: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  },

  age: {
    type: Number,
    min: 18,
    max: 60
  },

  role: {
    type: String,
    enum: ["Admin", "User"]
  },

  status: {
    type: String,
    default: "Active"
  }
});
```

---

# 12. MongoDB Atlas vs Local MongoDB

## Local MongoDB

Runs on your machine.

Connection:

```javascript
mongodb://localhost:27017/blogdb
```

Tools:

* MongoDB Community Server
* MongoDB Compass
* mongosh

---

## MongoDB Atlas

Cloud-hosted MongoDB service.

Connection:

```javascript
mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster.mongodb.net/blogdb
```

Advantages:

* Cloud hosting
* Automatic backups
* Monitoring tools
* Easy scalability
* Built-in replica sets

---

## Interview Answer

Local MongoDB runs on a developer's machine, while MongoDB Atlas is MongoDB's managed cloud platform providing hosting, monitoring, backups, and scalability.

---

# 13. Replica Sets (Concept)

A Replica Set is a group of MongoDB servers maintaining identical data.

```text
Primary
│
├── Secondary
└── Secondary
```

Purpose:

* High availability
* Data redundancy
* Automatic failover

---

## Interview Answer

A Replica Set is a group of MongoDB servers that maintain the same data to provide fault tolerance and high availability.

---

# 14. Sharding (Concept)

Sharding distributes data across multiple servers.

```text
Shard 1
Shard 2
Shard 3
```

Purpose:

* Horizontal scaling
* Increased storage capacity
* Improved performance

---

## Interview Answer

Sharding is MongoDB's horizontal scaling mechanism that distributes data across multiple servers to handle large datasets and heavy traffic.

---

# Blog App Schema Design

## Users Collection

```javascript
{
  _id,
  name,
  email,
  password
}
```

## Posts Collection

```javascript
{
  _id,
  title,
  content,
  author: ObjectId(User)
}
```

## Comments Collection

```javascript
{
  _id,
  post: ObjectId(Post),
  user: ObjectId(User),
  text,
  createdAt
}
```

---

## Design Justification

### User → Posts

Reference because:

* One user can create many posts
* Posts grow independently

### Post → Comments

Reference because:

* Comments can become very large
* Prevents document size issues
* Better scalability

